        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1Kings 5:2-11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", from which we learn that Huram or Hiram had first sent to congratulate Solomon upon his accession. The account here agrees generally with the parallel passage of the older work. The variations which present themselves only prove that the chronicler has made independent use of his sources.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Huram.—In Kings the name is spelt Hiram (1Kings 5:1-2; 1Kings 5:7) and Hirom (1Kings 5:10; 1Kings 5:18, Hebr.). (Comp. 1Chronicles 14:1.) Whether the Tyrian name Sirōmos (Herod. vii. 98) is another form of Hiram, as Bertheau supposes, is more than doubtful. It is interesting to find that the king of Tyre bore this name in the time of Tiglath-pileser II., to whom he paid tribute (B.C. 738), along with Menahem of Samaria. (Assyr. Hi-ru-um-mu, to which the Hîrôm of 1Kings 5:10; 1Kings 5:18 comes very near.)",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "Huram.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—In Kings the name is spelt ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "Hiram",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " (",
            "children": []
          },
          {
